node.text:
The exotic pet trade is a multi-million dollar industry, seen as a symbol of power and wealth. It’s no wonder influencers and celebrities use them as props in their own social media content. ⁣
⁣
Foeke Postma, an investigative journalist at Bellingcat, used fake Instagram accounts to follow people, reverse search images, geolocate pictures, and watch videos frame by frame to identify customers and exotic animal suppliers in Dubai.⁣
⁣
Postma set out to identify various animals through their spots, stripes and whiskers, tracing them back to anonymous individuals who were potentially engaged in the illegal leasing of wildlife. ⁣
⁣
In Super Users, we go down an internet rabbit hole to hear from people whose lives have become defined by their online presence.⁣
⁣
#vwn #viceworldnews

“I thought, I’m a trans woman. If I worked from outside the system, it’d be harder to voice out people’s aspirations.”⁣
⁣
In Muslim majority Indonesia, trans people are often not accepted in society as they are seen to contravene social norms. In Maumere, the largest city in Flores and a long way from Jakarta, it’s a different story. ⁣
⁣
Hendrika Mayora Victoria Kelan is a trans woman who overcame impossible odds to become Indonesia’s first trans official. She had left the Catholic clergy after coming to terms with her gender identity and had to make a living as a sex worker. Hendrika finally found acceptance after returning home where her community embraced her identity, and even nominated her as a candidate for public office. ⁣
⁣
Hendrika was elected as Head of the Regional Representative Council and her story has since become a source of inspiration for other trans women in her village.⁣
⁣
#vwn #viceworldnews

node.title: Meet Indonesia’s First Elected Trans Official

Memes are some of the most used and ubiquitous images on the internet. If you’ve used the internet over the last decade, there's no chance you’ve not seen one. ⁣
⁣
Political parties and groups of all persuasions have jumped on the meme culture bandwagon, but none more so than the far-right, who have weaponized irony to cloak their hateful ideologies and spread their memes far and wide into non-political spaces. ⁣
⁣
#vwn #viceworldnews

node.title: How the Far Right Use Memes to Recruit

node.text: “Who Let The Dogs Out” was ubiquitous in the early aughts - emanating from sports stadiums, parties, and radio speakers alike. But fewer people know the story behind the the group who performed it, @bahamenmusic, or the man who wrote it, @anslemdouglas64. The song’s unconventional journey spans from crowded baseball stadiums in Seattle to the sandy beaches of the Caribbean. VICE meets the key players involved in the incredible success of the song that left everyone asking, “Who Let the Dogs Out?”

node.title: The Story of 'Who Let The Dogs Out' by Baha Men

“Even with labels like ‘free-range’ and ‘organic’, we still find a lot of abuse and problems in those farms.”⁣
⁣
An undercover investigator for animal rights groups has spent the last 25 years covertly filming at factory farms across the UK and Europe. He’s seen animals beaten for not doing what the workers want and living half-dead in their own excrement. ⁣
⁣
This is the state of farms everywhere, even places making products labelled “local”, “organic” or "free-range".⁣
⁣
Informer is a series where we hear the anonymised confessions and insights of people in positions of power on the inside of important institutions.⁣
⁣

Most scam callers will do whatever it takes to steal your money. Many feel no guilt, but a small few know they are doing the wrong thing. Casey, a former scammer in India who is now undercover in call centers, works with investigators to gather evidence and help warn would-be scam victims.

In a series of candid interviews, Fakes, Frauds & Scammers relives some of the most audacious scams and fraudulent stunts of our time from the mouths of the perpetrators themselves. Whether it’s money, fame or simply an addiction to lying, we find out what motivated these tricksters and whether the highs, lows and ramifications were worth it in the end.

#vwn #viceworldnews

node.title: I Went Undercover in a Scam Call Center

⁣
Watch the full film on YouTube.⁣
⁣

node.text:
Backed into a corner of the ring, 18-year-old Jeanette Zacarias took a jab to the chin, then a hook to the temple. She held up her pink gloves to deflect a storm of punches until a feeble attempt at a counterattack left her open to a devastating blow that snapped her head back like a rubber band. Her death is raising questions about whether she should have been medically cleared to fight.⁠
⁠
Zacarias’s longtime trainer and manager, Luis Cruz, claims that her medical exams didn’t reveal any cause for concern, and that “everyone who gets into the ring knows that there is a risk of an accident.”
⁠
“They say that football is violent, or that hockey is violent, but the end game of those sports is to put the puck in the net or carry the ball into the end zone. In boxing, the end game is to cause the most damage possible to your opponent,” added Cruz. “You box to achieve goals that even being rich you might not reach, such as fame or global celebrity.”⁠
⁠
Link in bio for the full story.

node.text:
The exotic pet trade is a multi-million dollar industry, seen as a symbol of power and wealth. It’s no wonder influencers and celebrities use them as props in their own social media content. ⁣
⁣
Foeke Postma, an investigative journalist at Bellingcat, used fake Instagram accounts to follow people, reverse search images, geolocate pictures, and watch videos frame by frame to identify customers and exotic animal suppliers in Dubai.⁣
⁣
Postma set out to identify various animals through their spots, stripes and whiskers, tracing them back to anonymous individuals who were potentially engaged in the illegal leasing of wildlife. ⁣
⁣
In Super Users, we go down an internet rabbit hole to hear from people whose lives have become defined by their online presence.⁣
⁣
#vwn #viceworldnews

node.text:
If public transit isn't dangerous, it's a pandemic factory. If it's not a pandemic factory, it's stuffed with gross homeless people. If it's not gross, it's flooding in a storm. If it's not flooding in a storm, it's too crowded and smelly. And if it's not crowded and smelly, it's too empty and therefore scary. And if it's scary, it's dangerous, whether the statistics reflect that or not. ⁠
⁠
One thing is for sure: There's always something terribly wrong with public transit. ⁠
⁠
Homelessness, pandemics, crime, and extreme weather are all major issues in American life—hardly unique or limited to public transportation specifically. Still, they're often used as reasons to avoid public transit, as if that would be a fix for anything or anyone.⁠
⁠

node.text:
Involuntary treatment routinely fails; someone will get clean only when they want to get clean—and oftentimes, not even then.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
But as the opioid-overdose crisis has worsened, the use of both criminal and civil procedures to compel  drug users to get help, with the threat of “real” imprisonment if they do not comply, has become more popular across the United States.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
If Gov. Gavin Newsom signs into law a bill that unanimously passed the state Legislature earlier this month, Yolo County will also become the latest laboratory in an ongoing and widening nationwide experiment: Instead of sentencing drug users to jail, what if you sentenced them to rehab? More at link in bio 🔗⁠⁠

But as a 2016 review published in the International Journal of Drug Policy found, available "[e]vidence does not, on the whole, suggest improved outcomes related to compulsory treatment approaches, with some studies suggesting potential harms," including high potential for abuse within treatment centers. Instead, lawmakers should fund "non-compulsory" and evidence-based treatment. But rather than funding evidence- techniques like medication-assisted treatment, lawmakers and judges are just throwing more and more opioid users into "jail lite,' according to critics.'.

A Bangladeshi mother decided to take matters into her own hands when her 16-year-old daughter went missing. BY PALLAVI PUNDIR আিমেগ 001444592092'.

node.text:
On January 15,  Marium received a job offer from a man who was the family’s acquaintance. The supposed job offer was in a district near the border with India. Along the way, the recruiter handed Marium over to two other men. Once they reached the border, she realized what was happening. She convinced a man on the passenger boat—a stranger—to lend her his cellphone. She immediately called her mother. “I’m being taken to India! Save me!” Marium told Asiya, along with the names of her captors, before they snatched the phone from her.⁠
⁠
In February, the desperate mother contacted a man whom Marium had named as one of her traffickers. She told him she wanted a job abroad, too. He told her there was one in India. ⁠
⁠
Asiya then took out all her savings—Taka 60,000 ($703)—and left for the border.⁠
⁠
At least 20,000 Bangladeshi women and children are trafficked across the mostly-porous and unfenced border with India every year. Most never make it back. Read the full story at the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by VICE on September 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, child and text that says 'WAS ADOPTED BY AN INTERNATIONAL FAMILY BECAUSE OF CHINA'S ONE-CHILD POLICY" VICE'.

node.text:
From the 1940s onward China experienced a demographic boom which doubled the country’s population to almost one billion by the late 1970s. Desperate to prevent an excess 400 million births that would have compromised the country’s plans for financial growth, the Chinese government introduced its so-called one-child policy in 1979, limiting how the number of children couples were allowed to have by law. To avoid punishment, some felt forced to giving up their children, while other children listed for international adoption were forcibly taken away from their families. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The gallery features photographs by Youqine Lefèvre that explore the far-reaching consequences of China's disastrous birth program through her own adoption. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Link in bio for the full story. ⁠⁠

“I thought, I’m a trans woman. If I worked from outside the system, it’d be harder to voice out people’s aspirations.”⁣
⁣
In Muslim majority Indonesia, trans people are often not accepted in society as they are seen to contravene social norms. In Maumere, the largest city in Flores and a long way from Jakarta, it’s a different story. ⁣
⁣
Hendrika Mayora Victoria Kelan is a trans woman who overcame impossible odds to become Indonesia’s first trans official. She had left the Catholic clergy after coming to terms with her gender identity and had to make a living as a sex worker. Hendrika finally found acceptance after returning home where her community embraced her identity, and even nominated her as a candidate for public office. ⁣
⁣
Hendrika was elected as Head of the Regional Representative Council and her story has since become a source of inspiration for other trans women in her village.⁣
⁣

node.text: The Pacaso model is nothing if not novel. The company buys a home, lightly fixes up and furnishes it, and then creates an LLC with eight ownership stakes. Pacaso customers then purchase at least one-eighth of a share of the home. After that, Pacaso essentially becomes a corporate property manager, handling maintenance and scheduling. Link in bio for what it could mean for the future of home-owning 🔗⁠⁠
